Part I - an_analysis_of_features_which_have_the_most_influence_of_loan_outcomes¶

by Oludare Adekunle¶



Introduction¶

This dataset is data on loans from prosper. This data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others. Of these I selected a subset of 23 features and Loan status column. Of the subset a smaller subset of loan status, employment status, listing category, borrower rates and howeowners are used as they show lage variations across the factors being observed, Loan status.

Data set structure¶

There are 113936 observations, and 81 data columns of 3 boolean, 50 float64, 11 int64, and 17 object data types.

Main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I am most interested in the what determines a loan outcome and what determines borrower rate.

Features in the dataset which could help support my investigation into Loan Status outcomes?¶

For this purpose I will be investigating key features such as employment status, income range, listing categories, credit score, investors, loan term, occupation, borrower state, recommendations, investors, loan original amount, available bank card credit.

def redefine_past(x):
    """
    This function checks if the first four letters in a string are 'Past' and replaces that with 'Past due'
    """
    if x.startswith('Past'):
        return 'Past Due'
    else:
        return x

# univariate data exploration

def plot_univa(df, col, col_title, x, y):
    """
    This function creates a count plot with the count and percentage of each bar shown infront of the plot
    """
    type_count= df[col].value_counts()
    type_order= type_count.index
    type_sum= sum(type_count.values)

    plt.figure(figsize=[x, y])
    sb.countplot(data=df, y=col, color=sb.color_palette()[0], order=df[col].value_counts().index)
    plt.title(f'Count and Percentage Distribution of {col_title}', color='b')
    plt.ylabel(f'{col_title} Categories')
    plt.xlabel(None)
    plt.tick_params(axis='x', which='both', bottom=False, top=False, labelbottom=False)

    for i in range(type_count.shape[0]):
        count= type_count[i]
        pct_string= '{}\n({:0.2f}%)'.format(count, count/type_sum*100)
        plt.text(count+100, i, pct_string, va= 'center')
        
plot_univa(loan_df_ol, 'loan_status', 'Loan Status', 20, 10)

Conclusions¶


At the beginning of this journey, I set out to explore trends that cut across the different categories of the Loan Status. Since there were a whole lot of features with which I could use to find trends, I intuitively picked the following features.
1. Listing Creation Date 2. Term 3. Loan Status
4. Borrower Apr 5. Borrower Rate 6. Listing Category
7. Borrower State 8. Occupation 9. Employment Status
10. Employment Status Duration 11. Is Borrower Home Owner 12. Credit Score Range Lower
13. Credit Score Range Upper 14. Revolving Credit Balance 15. Bank Card Utilization
16. Available Bank Card Credit 17. Debt To Income Ratio 18. Income Range
19. Income Verifiable 20. Stated Monthly Income 21. Monthly Loan Payment
22. Recommendations 23. Investors 24. Loan Original Amount

From the exploration of these features, I found that the average borrower rate of Loans completed and final payments being processed was generally lower when compared to those that defaulted or charged off.

Furthermore, when the borrower rate across Loan Status is compared with if borrower is a home owner, I found out that generally, home owners are offered loans at a lower rate and observations across the completed category are concentrated around the lower borrower rate. However, across the defaulted category and this holds aprroximately true for all Loan status categories except the defaulted category where I find out that, non home owners defaults observations concentrate around high borrower rates while for home owners defaults were concentrated around those with Low Borrower rate.

Also, I found out that the most common reason for which loans are collect is for debt reconsolidations which forms over 50% of the entire data. the next two: Not disclosed and other are non specific and as such cannot be determined, thus I will say the next specific reasons for which loans are taken are listed below:

S/No Reason for Loan % of Observation
1. Debt Reconsolidation 51.18
2. Not Available 14.89
3. Other 9.21
4. Home Improvement 6.52
5. Business 6.31

in almost all loan status category, I found that the reason for which our observation access loans the most is for debt consolidation. However, when we look at the defaulted category where we expect to find similar trend of debt consolidation topping the list we find that, observations where there is no record of what the loan is used for tops the chart.

In conclusion, the insights I derived from the above analysis and explorations are listed below:

  1. Low borrower rates promotes loan repayment completion of borrowers.
  2. Employed borrowers are most likely to complete their loan repayments, while borrowers who do not state their employment status are most likely to default or not complete their loan repayments
  3. Borrowers who state their listing as "Debt Consolidation" tend to be most apt at completing their loan repayments when compared with other listings while those who list "Not available" tend to mostly default and not repay their loans
  4. Regarless of home owner status, lower borrow rates postively influences borrowers to complete their loan repayments.
